'''''Pinball Quest''''' is a [[1989 in video games|1989]] [[pinball]] [[video game]] developed by [[Tose (company)|Tose]]{{CN|date=August 2021}} and published by [[Jaleco]]. Released for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], ''Pinball Quest'' was unusual at the time of its release for its "unique"<ref name="nintendopower">{{cite magazine |title=Pinball Quest |url=https://archive.org/details/Nintendo_Power_Issue001-Issue127/Nintendo%20Power%20Issue%20014%20July-August%201990/page/n89/mode/2up?q=pinball |access-date=1 August 2021 |magazine=Nintendo Power |issue=July-August 1990}}</ref> mash-up of pinball and [[Role-playing video game|role-playing game]] (RPG) mechanics, and it is considered the "first ever RPG pinball game."<ref name="scullion">{{cite book |last1=Scullion |first1=Chris |title=The NES Encyclopedia |date=2019 |publisher=Pen & Sword Books |isbn=9781526737809 |page=145 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IE8IEAAAQBAJ |access-date=1 August 2021}}</ref>
==Game play==
[[File:PinballQuestNESWitchBoss.png|left|thumb|256px|Fighting a boss battle]]
The game includes four modes: a story-driven "RPG mode" as well as "Circus," "Viva! Golf," and "Pop! Pop!"

Circus (a [[slot machine]]-themed game) and Viva! Golf (a [[whack-a-mole]]-style game) are additional single-player modes. Pop! Pop! is a sports-themed multiplayer mode that can be played by up to 4 players.
===RPG mode ===
In RPG mode, the player controls the silver pinball and progresses through a six-level castle to rescue Princess Bali from Beezelbub, the "Dark Lord of the Machine." As in traditional pinball, [[Flipper (pinball)|flippers]] are used to keep the ball in the [[Pinball#Playfield|playfield]] and accomplish objectives, such as hitting targets or defeating an enemy. 

During game play, the player earns gold which can be spent at the Black Market, a store run by imps. At the Black Market, players can purchase upgraded flippers and [[Pinball#Switches, gates, and stoppers|stoppers]].

Below are the six "RPG mode" stages and the notable characters or features in each stage as listed in the instruction manual.
# '''Tomb''' (the Captain's Spirit, skeletons)
# '''Gate''' (Ziffroo the witch, demon dogs)
# '''Goblins''' (goblin kids, goblin guards)
# '''River''' ("[[turtle|toitles]]," "Wheel O' Luck," dark knights)
# '''Harpy''' (harpy, demon guards)
# '''Throne room''' (Beezelbub)

==Reception==
Retrospective reviews of ''Pinball Quest'' focus on the novelty of its RPG elements. The game has been called a "curious mix of genres",<ref name="scullion" /> with some reviewers describing it in more extreme terms, stating it is "among the most bizarre genre hybrids in the history of video games"<ref name="HG101">{{cite web |title=Pinball Quest |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/pinball-quest/ |website=Hardcore Gaming 101 |access-date=1 August 2021}}</ref> and a "baffling experiment."<ref name="defunctgames">{{cite web |last1=Lachel |first1=Cyril |title=Pinball Quest |url=http://www.defunctgames.com/review/1108/pinball-quest |website=Defunct Games |access-date=1 August 2021}}</ref>

